# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aboyne-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Aboyne has many businesses, including a Co-Op supermarket, several hairdressers, a butcher, a newsagent, an Indian restaurant and a post office.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Originally, there was a railway station in the village, but it was closed on 18 June 1966.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The station now contains some shops and the tunnel running under the village is now home to a firearms club.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The market-day in Aboyne was known as *Fèill Mhìcheil* (Scottish Gaelic for "Michael's Fair").
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The name "Aboyne" is derived from "Oboyne", first recorded in 1260, in turn derived from the Gaelic words "abh", "bo", and "fionn", meaning "[place by] white cow river".
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The village of Aboyne was founded by Charles Gordon, 1st Earl of Aboyne in 1671, who, in the same year, rebuilt the west wing of Aboyne Castle.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The siting of the castle itself is related to the limited number of the crossings of the Mounth of the Grampian Mountains to the south.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] In 1715 Aboyne was the scene of a tinchal, or great hunt, organised by John Erskine, sixth Earl of Mar, on 3 September, as a cover for the gathering of Jacobite nobles and lairds to discuss a planned Jacobite rising.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The uprising began three days later in Braemar.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The former Aboyne Public School was used as a secondary school to the local area, but was notably used during WWII as an evacuee station for those coming from Glasgow.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Local Aboyne children were educated in the morning and the evacuee children were educated in the afternoon.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Any overflow evacuees were passed on to the nearby church hall, and as many as 1,250 were evacuated to the Deeside area in 1939.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] An eighth-century Christian presence in Aboyne is attested by a Pictish stone cross called the Formaston Stone.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The slab is inscribed with Ogham characters which have been transliterated as “MAQQOoiTALLUORRH | NxHHTVROBBACCxNNEVV.” These are the Pictish names Talorc (TALLUORRH) and Nehht (NxHHT), both of which were names of kings.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] 732) was said by Bede to have accepted the Christian faith in response to the teachings of Adamnan, abbot of Iona, eventually bringing his people to Christianity as well.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Aboyne's first church was dedicated to Adamnan, and it was at the burial ground of this church where the Formaston Stone was first discovered.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The stone was eventually removed to Aboyne Castle and is currently exhibited in the Inverurie Museum.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] In 1237, Alexander II granted the Knights Templar a charter of liberty to acquire lands in Scotland, and Walter Byset, Lord of Aboyne, gave the Templar preceptory the church of Aboyne.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Then, between 1239 and 1249, the church was conveyed to the Templars *adproprier usus* by Ralph, Bishop of Aberdeen.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] According to the terms of the charter, the Templars would take charge of the temporalities of the church and maintain a vicar there, while the bishop retained authority in spiritual matters.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] King Alexander II confirmed the donation on 15 April 1242, and Pope Alexander IV, in 1277, the same year that John of Annan, chaplain to Alexander III, was appointed vicar.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Aboyne, along with other Templar possessions in Scotland, was held by the Torphichen Preceptory in the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries and remained so until the Reformation.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] In 1761, a new parish church was constructed in Aboyne, under the patronage of the Marquess of Huntly; then, in 1842, another church was built on the site of the eighteenth-century structure, and in 1929 at the Union of the Established Church, it was formally dedicated to St.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Machar's was joined with the United Free Church, and fifty years later, was linked with the parish church of Dinnet, a linkage which led to the 1993 union between the two, which is now known as the Aboyne-Dinnet Parish Church.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] In 2006, Aboyne-Dinnet was linked with the parish church at Cromar.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Aboyne has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*), similar to most of the United Kingdom.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Due to its high inland position in Scotland, Aboyne can record some very low temperatures and some high snowfall.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Conversely, temperatures can reach exceptional values for the latitude, particularly during the winter months due to the foehn effect; it holds the March record for the highest temperature in Scotland, with 23.6 °C (74.5 °F) on 27 March 2012.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The February record for Scotland was broken on 21 February 2019 at 18.3 °C.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] In summer, when tourists visit, the number of people and vehicles increases dramatically.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The Highland Games on the Village Green features in August.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The green includes facilities for rugby and football and a play park as well as Aboyne Canoe Clubs storage facility 'The Canoe Cathedral'.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The British Royal Family are residents in nearby Balmoral Castle during the Summer.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Outdoor pursuits include golf, walking, cycling, mountain biking trails, kayaking, canoeing and gliding from the airfield just outside the village.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Aboyne has become popular with gliding enthusiasts from Britain and Europe due to its suitable air currents (due to the surrounding terrain).
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The airfield has two parallel tarmac runways running east–west, a webcam and small weather-monitoring centre on its premises.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Aboyne contains a mountain biking facility at Aboyne Bike Park located in the Bellwood.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The old Aboyne Curling Club had its own private railway station, Aboyne Curling Pond railway station, at the Loch of Aboyne.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The close by pass of Ballater is a rock-climbing area.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The village of Dinnet is a few miles west and is the first being located inside the Cairngorms National Park.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Walkers and cyclists can ascend Mount Keen by cycling as far as they can from Glen Tanar forest before walking to the summit.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] There are two schools, Aboyne Academy and a primary school.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The academy has around 650 pupils, about a quarter from Aboyne itself, with the remaining three quarters from surrounding villages.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The primary school has around 240 children and also contains a nursery with around 30 children.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The school has access to a full-size swimming pool and gym run by the adjacent Deeside Community Centre.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Belwade Farm, a horse sanctuary, is situated nearby.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] A small stone circle is situated in the village, with several other megaliths nearby, notably the Tomnaverie stone circle, which is also the site of a disused Royal Observer Corps monitoring post.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Aboyne is twinned with Martignas-sur-Jalle, a commune in Nouvelle-Aquitaine in the southwest of France.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] The village is served by the 201/202 bus service operated by Stagecoach which provides a regular bus service to Aberdeen, Banchory, Ballater and Braemar.
[src:aboyne-hospital/aboyne] Ember's E11 from Aberdeen to Dundee also serves the village (prebooked).
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Born at Clarence House, Anne was educated at Benenden School and began carrying out official royal duties in early adulthood.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] A distinguished equestrian, she won one gold medal at the 1971 and two silver medals at the 1975 European Eventing Championships.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1976, she became the first member of the British royal family to compete in the Olympic Games.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She has been a member of the International Olympic Committee since 1988.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne continues to undertake engagements and official duties on behalf of the monarch – she has attended more than 20,000 such events since commencing royal duties in 1968.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She presently serves as patron or honorary president of more than 300 organisations, including WISE, Riders for Health, Carers Trust, and Transaid.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Her charitable work focuses primarily on sport, science, disability, and health in developing countries.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She has been closely associated with Save the Children for over 50 years and has visited numerous projects supported by the organisation worldwide.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1973, Anne married Captain Mark Phillips; the couple separated in 1989 and divorced in 1992.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] They have two children, Peter Phillips and Zara Tindall.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1992, she married Commander (now Vice Admiral) Sir Timothy Laurence, whom she met during his service as an equerry to Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne was born at 11:50 am on 15 August 1950 at Clarence House in London, during the reign of her maternal grandfather, King George VI.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She was the second child and only daughter of Princess Elizabeth, Duchess of Edinburgh (later Queen Elizabeth II), and Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] A 21-gun salute in Hyde Park marked the occasion.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne was baptised in the Music Room at Buckingham Palace on 21 October 1950, by the Archbishop of York, Cyril Garbett.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] At the time of her birth, she was third in the line of succession to the British throne, behind her mother and elder brother, Charles (later King Charles III).
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She rose to second in 1952 after her grandfather's death and her mother's accession; she is currently 18th in line.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] A governess, Catherine Peebles, was appointed to oversee the early education of Anne and her brothers, Charles, Andrew, and Edward.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Peebles supervised Anne's lessons at Buckingham Palace.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Owing to her young age, Anne did not attend her mother's coronation in June 1953.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In May 1959, a Girl Guides unit, the 1st Buckingham Palace Guide Company, incorporating the Holy Trinity Brompton Brownie pack, was re-formed specifically so that Anne, like her mother and her aunt Princess Margaret before her, could socialise with girls her own age.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The company remained active until 1963, when Anne left for boarding school.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She enrolled at Benenden School in 1963, leaving in 1968 with six GCE O-Levels and two A-Levels.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She began undertaking royal engagements in 1969, at the age of 18.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1970, Anne briefly had a relationship with Andrew Parker Bowles, who later married Camilla Shand.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Camilla subsequently became the second wife and queen consort of Anne's elder brother, Charles III.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne was also briefly linked to the Olympic equestrian Richard Meade.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In spring 1971, Anne finished fourth at the Rushall Horse Trials.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] At the age of 21, she won the individual title at the European Eventing Championship on her home-bred horse Doublet, and was voted the BBC Sports Personality of the Year for 1971.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She also rode winners in horse racing, competing in the Grand Military Steeplechase at Sandown Park Racecourse and the Diamond Stakes at Royal Ascot.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] For more than five years, Anne competed with the British eventing team, winning silver medals in both the individual and team disciplines at the 1975 European Eventing Championship.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The following year, she took part in the 1976 Olympic Games in Montreal as a member of the British team, riding the Queen's horse Goodwill in Eventing.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne suffered a concussion halfway through the cross-country course but remounted and completed the event; she later stated that she had no memory of making the remaining jumps.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The British team subsequently withdrew from the competition after two horses were injured.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She finished fourth at the Badminton Horse Trials in 1974 and sixth in 1979, having competed in the event five times between 1971 and 1979.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1985, she rode in a charity race at the Epsom Derby, finishing fourth.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne served as president of the Fédération Équestre Internationale from 1986 until 1994.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] On 5 February 1987, she became the first member of the royal family to appear as a contestant on a television quiz show when she took part in the BBC panel game *A Question of Sport*.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She has been a patron of the Riding for the Disabled Association since 1971 and became its president in 1985, a role she continues to hold.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In June 2024, Anne was taken to Southmead Hospital in Bristol with minor injuries and concussion, believed to have been caused by an impact with a horse's legs or head.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne met Mark Phillips, a lieutenant in the 1st Queen's Dragoon Guards, in 1968 at a party for horse enthusiasts.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Their engagement was announced on 29 May 1973.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] On 14 November 1973, the couple married at Westminster Abbey in a televised ceremony watched by an estimated 100 million people.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] They subsequently took up residence at Gatcombe Park.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Media reports stated that Phillips was offered an earldom, as was then customary for untitled men marrying into the royal family, but he and Anne declined the honour.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] As a result, their children were born without titles.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The couple had two children: Peter (born 1977) and Zara Phillips (born 1981).
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne and Phillips have five grandchildren.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] On 31 August 1989, Anne and Phillips announced their intention to separate; the couple had been rarely seen together in public, and both had been romantically linked with other people.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] They shared custody of their children and initially stated that "there were no plans for divorce." On 13 April 1992, the Palace announced that Anne had filed for divorce, which was finalised ten days later.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne met Timothy Laurence, a commander in the Royal Navy, while he was serving on the Royal Yacht *Britannia*.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Their relationship developed in early 1989, three years after Laurence had been appointed an equerry to the Queen.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1989, the existence of private letters from Laurence to Anne was revealed by *The Sun* newspaper.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The couple married at Crathie Kirk, near Balmoral Castle in Scotland, on 12 December 1992.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The ceremony was conducted by Molly Croll, the local Ballater registrar.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Approximately 30 guests attended the private service.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Unlike the Church of England at the time, the Church of Scotland did not regard marriage as a binding sacrament and therefore permitted the remarriage of divorced persons under certain circumstances.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] For the wedding, Anne wore a white jacket over a "demure, cropped-to-the-knee dress" and a spray of white flowers in her hair.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Her engagement ring was described as "a cabochon sapphire flanked by three small diamonds on each side".
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] After the ceremony, the couple and their guests travelled to Craigowan Lodge for a private reception.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Laurence did not receive a peerage, although he was knighted in 2011.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] On 20 March 1974, Anne and Mark Phillips were returning to Buckingham Palace when a car forced their Rolls-Royce to stop on Pall Mall.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The car’s driver, Ian Ball, jumped out and began firing a pistol.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Inspector James Beaton, Anne's personal protection officer, left the car to shield her and attempted to disarm Ball.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Beaton's Walther PPK jammed, and he was shot, as was Anne's chauffeur, Alex Callender, when he tried to intervene.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Brian McConnell, a nearby tabloid journalist, also attempted to help and was shot in the chest.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Ball approached Anne's car and told her that he intended to kidnap her and hold her for ransom, the amount reported variously as £2 million or £3 million, which he claimed he intended to donate to the National Health Service.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] When Ball ordered Anne to get out of the car, she replied, "Not bloody likely!" She reportedly considered striking him.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1983, she discussed the incident on *Parkinson*, saying she had been 'scrupulously polite' to Ball because she thought it would be "silly to be too rude at that stage".
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne eventually exited from the opposite side of the limousine, as did her lady-in-waiting, Rowena Brassey.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] A passing pedestrian, former boxer Ron Russell, punched Ball and led Anne away from the scene.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Police Constable Michael Hills then arrived; he too was shot, but had already called assistance.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Detective Constable Peter Edmonds responded, pursued Ball, and arrested him.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Beaton, who had been Anne's sole bodyguard, later reflected on royal security at the time, saying "I had nothing… There was no back-up vehicle.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The training was non-existent; but then again, [we thought] nothing was going to happen.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] They are highly specialised now, highly trained." Following the attack, the practice of assigning only a single protection officer was ended, and the Walther PPK was replaced.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Beaton, Hills, Callender, and McConnell were hospitalised and recovered from their injuries.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] For his defence of Anne, Beaton was awarded the George Cross by the Queen, who was visiting Indonesia when the incident occurred; Hills and Russell were awarded the George Medal, and Callender, McConnell, and Edmonds were awarded the Queen's Gallantry Medal.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne visited Beaton in hospital to thank him.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] It was widely reported that the Queen paid off Russell's mortgage, but this was untrue: Russell stated in 2020 that a police officer had suggested it might happen, leading him to stop making payments and nearly lose his home after four months.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Ball pleaded guilty to attempted murder and kidnapping.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] After being diagnosed with schizophrenia, he was detained in mental hospitals for 45 years and released in 2019.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 2025, he claimed innocence, stating that the attempt had been intended to fail as part of a stunt.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The attempted kidnapping is the subject of the Granada Television docudrama *To Kidnap a Princess* (2006) and inspired storylines in Tom Clancy's novel *Patriot Games*.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne undertakes a wide range of duties and engagements on behalf of the sovereign.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] MacLeod, the then Canadian Secretary to the Queen, said of her in 2014: "Her credo is, 'Keep me busy.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] I'm here to meet as many people as possible'." In December 2017, it was reported that Anne had carried out the most official engagements that year of any member of the royal family, including the Queen.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Among her overseas visits, she has toured Norway, Jamaica, Germany, Austria, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne's first public engagement took place in 1969, when she opened an educational and training centre in Shropshire.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She travels abroad on behalf of the United Kingdom up to three times a year.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She began undertaking overseas visits after leaving secondary school, and accompanied her parents on a state visit to Austria in the same year.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1990, she became the first member of the royal family to make an official visit to the Soviet Union, travelling there as a guest of President Mikhail Gorbachev and his government.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In August 2016, Anne returned to Russia to visit the city of Arkhangelsk for the 75th anniversary of Operation Dervish, one of the first Arctic convoys of World War II.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The following month, she developed a chest infection and was required to cancel official engagements.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In late October 2016, she undertook a two-day study tour of the Malaysian state of Sarawak.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In April 2022, Anne and her husband toured Australia and Papua New Guinea to mark the Queen's Platinum Jubilee.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] On 12 September 2022, at St Giles' Cathedral in Edinburgh, Anne became the first woman to participate in a Vigil of the Princes, standing guard by her mother's coffin.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She repeated the vigil at Westminster Hall on 16 September.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] It was later revealed that she had been the informant at her mother's death at Balmoral, signing the death certificate alongside the attending doctor.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] On 21 April 2026, Anne opened the Queen Elizabeth II Garden on the centenary of her mother's birth.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne is involved with more than 200 charities and organisations in an official capacity.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She works extensively with Save the Children, serving as its president from 1970 to 2017 and as patron since 2017.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She has visited the organisation's projects in Bangladesh, Sierra Leone, South Africa, Mozambique, Ethiopia, and Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In recognition of her humanitarian work, she was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize in 1990 by Kenneth Kaunda, President of Zambia.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She founded The Princess Royal Trust for Carers in 1991.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] John Ambulance as Commandant-in-Chief of St.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] John Ambulance Cadets has supported the development of many young people, and she attends the annual Grand Prior Award Reception.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 2021, she became patron of Mercy Ships, an international charity that operates the world's largest non-governmental hospital ships.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne serves as a British representative in the International Olympic Committee as an administrator and as a member of the London Organising Committee for the Olympic Games.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She is president of the British Olympic Association and represented Great Britain on the International Olympic Committee at the 2014 Sochi Winter Olympics in Russia.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1985, she became president of the Riding for the Disabled Association after serving as its patron for fourteen years.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She maintains a close relationship with student sport and is patron of British Universities and Colleges Sport.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Following the retirement of the Queen Mother in 1981, Anne was elected by graduates of the University of London as Chancellor, a position she has held since that year.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She served as president of BAFTA from 1973 to 2001.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Throughout May 1996, she served as Her Majesty's High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland, and held the post again in 2017.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 2007, she was appointed by the Queen as Grand Master of the Royal Victorian Order, a role previously held by her grandmother.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She is a Royal Fellow of both the Royal Society and the Academy of Medical Sciences, becoming the latter's first Royal Fellow.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] As of 2022, the Royal Society has four Royal Fellows: Anne; William, Prince of Wales; Edward, Duke of Kent; and King Charles.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne was elected Chancellor of the University of Edinburgh with effect from 31 March 2011, succeeding her father, who stepped down in 2010.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Also in 2011, she became president of City and Guilds of London Institute, Master of the Corporation of Trinity House, and president of the Royal Society of Arts, all in succession to her father.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She has long served as president of the Commonwealth Study Conference, an initiative founded by him.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 2023, she succeeded the Duke of Kent as president of the Commonwealth War Graves Commission.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne is the patron of Transaid, a charity founded by Save the Children and the Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport that aims to provide safe and sustainable transport in developing countries.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She is also the patron of WISE, an organisation that encourages young women to pursue careers in science, engineering, and construction.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She has been patron of the Royal National Children's Foundation since 2002, and of the industrial heritage museum, Aerospace Bristol since 2016.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 2022, Anne was named honorary chair of National Lighthouse Museum's Illuminating Future Generations campaign, a project established to raise funds for the museum's gallery space.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1986, she was appointed Master of the Worshipful Company of Carmen.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 2001, she became Master of the Worshipful Company of Farmers.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 2017, Anne became Prime Warden of the Worshipful Company of Fishmongers and a Governor of Gresham's School.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 2025, she was announced as patron of Friends of the Elderly, taking on the role previously held by Queen Elizabeth II for more than 60 years.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne has been described as the royal family's "trustiest anchor" and a "beacon of good, old-fashioned public service" and has carried out more than 20,000 engagements since her 18th birthday.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In her early adulthood, she was characterised as a "royal renegade" for choosing to forgo titles for her children despite being the "spare to the heir".
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The media often labelled the young Anne "aloof" and "haughty", earning her the nickname "her royal rudeness".
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She attracted controversy in 1982 when she told photographers to "naff off" at the Badminton Horse Trials.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] *Vanity Fair* wrote that Anne "has a reputation for having inherited her father's famously sharp tongue and waspish wit".
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] So my early trips were really important." She has frequently been named the "hardest working royal", and carried out 11,088 engagements between 2002 and 2022, more than any other member of the royal family.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne remains one of Britain's most popular royals.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] *Telegraph* editor Camilla Tominey has called her a "national treasure", describing her as "one of the great English eccentrics", whose work ethic underpins her public regard.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Tominey wrote that Anne's public role is a "contradiction of both protocol taskmaster and occasional rule-breaker".
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne reportedly "insists on doing her own make-up and hair" and sometimes drives herself to engagements, having pleaded guilty to two separate speeding offences after running late.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 1974, she became the first member of the royal family to hold an HGV licence, later saying "I was considering earning my living by driving, and with my HGV licence, I don't mind spending time on my own behind the wheel".
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She does not shake hands with the public during walkabouts, explaining, "the theory was that you couldn't shake hands with everybody, so don't start." Members of the public have seen her "mending fences at Gatcombe" and "queuing up for the Portaloos" at her daughter's horse competitions.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Her reputation is also linked to her advocacy for causes outside the mainstream, such as Wetwheels Foundation's commitment to accessible sailing and the National Lighthouse Museum.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] On her 60th and 70th birthdays, both the BBC and *Vanity Fair* asked whether she intended to retire; she denied it on both occasions, citing her parents' example and her commitment to her duty.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Her public personality has been described as "not suffering fools lightly" while maintaining a "still-impressive level of grace and courtesy".
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] British *Vogue* editor Edward Enninful has said that "Princess Anne is a true style icon and was all about sustainable fashion before the rest of us really knew what that meant".
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Her style has been noted for its timelessness; she relies largely on British fashion brands, with tweed and tailored suits as her hallmarks.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She is known for recycling outfits, including a floral-print dress worn both to the wedding of the Prince of Wales in 1981 and the wedding of Lady Rose Windsor in 2008.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne is patron of the UK Fashion and Textile Association.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She has been noted for wearing "bold patterns and vibrant pops of colour".
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Her clothing choices often reflect her equestrian interests and the practicality required by her fast-paced schedule.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In the 1970s and 1980s, she was frequently photographed in trends such as puff sleeves, cardigans, bright floral patterns, and multicoloured stripes.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She is also one of the few women in the royal family to wear a military uniform.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] According to *The Guardian*, she is "rarely seen without a brooch" at royal events.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Her millinery has included jockey caps and hats in multiple colours and bold patterns.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She presented the Queen Elizabeth II award for British design at London Fashion Week in 2020.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne has appeared on three British *Vogue* covers: the September 1971 issue at age 21, and the May and November 1973 issues marking her engagement to Mark Phillips.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She was featured in the cover story of the May 2020 issue of *Vanity Fair*.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In 2024, *Tatler* included her among the most glamorous European royals.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne is the first member of the royal family to have been convicted of a criminal offence.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] In November 2002, she pleaded guilty to one charge of having a dog dangerously out of control, an offence under the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991, and was fined £500.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne is the seventh Princess Royal, an appellation granted only to the eldest daughter of the Sovereign.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] The previous holder was Princess Mary, Countess of Harewood, the daughter of King George V and Anne's great-aunt.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne is a Royal Knight Companion of the Most Noble Order of the Garter, an Extra Knight of the Most Ancient and Most Noble Order of the Thistle, Grand Master and Dame Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order, and a Dame Grand Cross of the Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of St John of Jerusalem.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] She is a recipient of the Royal Family Order of Elizabeth II, the Royal Family Order of Charles III, and serves as a Personal Aide-de-Camp to the Sovereign.
[src:aboyne-hospital/anne-princess-royal] Anne's ancestry can be traced as far back as Cerdic, King of Wessex (519–534).
[src:aboyne-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Chalmers Hospital was founded by Alexander Chalmers (died 11 August 1835), a merchant of Banff, who left the whole of his estate to be applied, upon the death of his wife, towards funding and building a hospital for the people in the Royal Burgh of Banff.
[src:aboyne-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Mrs Chalmers died in 1861, and Chalmers Hospital opened on 19 July 1864.
[src:aboyne-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The original 'deed of mortification' set out that this was for any destitute sick persons born, domiciled or resident in the Banff area, although in 1929 the trustees successfully petitioned for the removal of this restriction.
[src:aboyne-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Some major redevelopment work began in October 2008, after the hospital attracted criticism for not being up to date, with some of the interior features having been there since the Second World War.
[src:aboyne-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital remained open during the work, although the Findlater ward services were moved to Campbell Hospital in Portsoy until the Findlater ward was refurbished, and Seafield and Deveron ward were merged.
[src:aboyne-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The midwifery unit was demolished and rebuilt to provide modern facilities.
[src:aboyne-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Numerous other internal changes were also made inside, including X-ray facilities being moved to a different area of the building.
[src:aboyne-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The redevelopment also provided upgraded facilities for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy and podiatry.
[src:aboyne-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The completion of the redevelopment was recognised with a visit by the Princess Royal in March 2012.
[src:aboyne-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital is supported by GPs from Banff, Gamrie, Deveron, Macduff, Portsoy and Aberchirder Medical Practices.
[src:aboyne-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] The facility, which was designed by William Smith, was established as an infectious diseases hospital in 1874.
[src:aboyne-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] It was significantly expanded in 1895 and a new nurses' home was completed in 1931.
[src:aboyne-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] During the 1964 Aberdeen typhoid outbreak, over 400 cases were diagnosed and the patients were quarantined at the City Hospital and Woodend Hospital, although no fatalities resulted.
